// Predicate lookup with multi-object superposition.
//
// Specialization of the knowledge-graph demo to the case where the
// same (subject, predicate) key appears with multiple objects. Under
// VSA superposition, the unbound result is a *sum* of all matching
// objects, so each member object has non-trivial cosine similarity
// to the recovered vector while non-members have near-zero cosine.
//
// Graph:
//   alice likes cats
//   alice likes dogs        <- alice likes two things
//   bob   likes fish
//   bob   likes birds       <- bob likes two things
//   carol likes hamsters
//
// Query (alice, likes) should recover a superposition of cats + dogs;
// similarity to cats and dogs is HIGH, similarity to fish/birds/
// hamsters is LOW.
//
// The demo returns the similarity score between the recovered vector
// and a candidate object — the smoke test checks the ordering
// (members rank above non-members).

// --- Subjects ---
vector alice = basis_vector("alice");
vector bob   = basis_vector("bob");
vector carol = basis_vector("carol");

// --- Predicate ---
vector likes = basis_vector("likes");

// --- Objects ---
vector cats     = basis_vector("cats");
vector dogs     = basis_vector("dogs");
vector fish     = basis_vector("fish");
vector birds    = basis_vector("birds");
vector hamsters = basis_vector("hamsters");

// --- Graph: five triples, bundled. Two (subject, predicate) keys
// have multiple objects. ---
vector graph = bundle(
    bind(cats,     bind(alice, likes)),
    bind(dogs,     bind(alice, likes)),
    bind(fish,     bind(bob,   likes)),
    bind(birds,    bind(bob,   likes)),
    bind(hamsters, bind(carol, likes))
);

// Score how well (subject, predicate) implies object — cosine
// similarity of the recovered bundle to the candidate object.
function scalar fits(vector subject, vector predicate, vector object) {
    vector recovered = unbind(predicate, unbind(subject, graph));
    return similarity(recovered, object);
}
